<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Service delivery</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence  submitted by the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">London</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold"> Borough of Newham</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">1. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Introduction</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.25pt; text-indent:-35.25pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1.1</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In Newham we believe in promoting resilience</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> among our residents</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">By this we mean that residents should be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">enabled to posses</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> a set of skills and hav</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> access to the resources that allow </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">them</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to negotiate challenges, overcome the more difficult circumstances many of our residents experience, and take up opportunities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> that come their way</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.25pt; text-indent:-35.25pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1.2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">E</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">mployment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> at the heart of our conception of economic resilience, and our local </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">employment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> scheme Workplace </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">helped 5</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,000 people find jobs </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">last year alone</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. We recognise that the perception, and in some cases reality, of a benefit trap is extremely damaging and can ac</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t as a major barrier to people taking up or progressing in work. We welcome the principle behind Universal Credit of a single taper on benefit removal as paid income increases.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.25pt; text-indent:-35.25pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1.3</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">However, we are extremely concerned that the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">wider </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">implementation of welfa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">re reforms </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">could</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> be disastrous for low income families, for whom in many cases it will be impossible to provide affordable accommodation. We are particularly concerned about the impact of the benefit cap and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the spare room subsidy (known as the ‘bedroom ta</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">x’)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. We do not feel that the Government’s approach to implementing reforms has shown a joined-up approach between departments.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1.4</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The changes have transferred c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">onsiderable risk onto </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ocal </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">uthorities and come with a backdrop of benefit cuts that will </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">leave more people in poverty in 2020 than at present</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> As one of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">’s most deprived boroughs, Newham is committed to building a mixed community where people from different incomes and backgrounds</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> live together cohesive</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ly</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The London Borough of Newham</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> u</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ltimately </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">believe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> that certain key aspects of the government’s welfare reforms will damage our efforts to ensure residents are economically resilient throughout times of hardship.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1.5</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The reforms </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">require an</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> increas</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in Council resources at a time when bu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">dgets are being cut.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> W</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e are concerned that support and resources offered to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">help </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">residents through the transition are not taking into account levels of need in each area.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> We are predicting a steep rise in arrears from tenants, increased pressure on social </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">services, and high numbers of requests for direct payments from tenants.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1.6</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Additionally, while in principle we are supportive of a gradual rollout of Universal Credit, the lack of clarity on the timescales for certain reforms has </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">resulted in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> uncertainty over when the changes are likely to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">affect Newham</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">'s tenants</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">2. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Local Housing Allowance (LHA) reforms</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2.1</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It is important that the private rented sector is affordable for all of our residents, including young single people, families with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">children and disabled people. However, o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ur on the ground experience is that rising rents combined with welfare reforms are making an increasing proportion of our rented sector unavailable to people who are in receipt of LHA. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2.2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The DWP’s own research ha</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s found that 94% of the shortfall resulting from overall LHA changes has fallen on tenants. Only 6% has fallen on landlords.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> As it is clear that these changes are reducing individuals’ incomes, we feel it is reasonable to target available funding at areas</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> with the greatest shortfall between LHA rates and market rents. This will most effectively mitigate severe impacts on individuals already in housing, which may not be achieved through a focus on the proportion of the market available. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2.3</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Our operationa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">l experience has identified two particular barriers to residents who need to claim Housing Benefit accessing private sector tenancies. The first is the problem that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">many of the properties rented at under the 30th percentile of rents are not available</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> cl</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">aimants. This is because some landlords are unwilling to rent to them due to a range of issues from negative perceptions, to the time taken to regain possession of a property occupied by a Housing Benefit claimant, to concerns about future affordability. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2.4</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The second barrier is that the private rented sector in Newham is used by a number of other central </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> local authorities as temporary accommodation for</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> homeless</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> residents. These authorities are able to offer high lump-sum incentive payments to lan</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">dlords to secure Newham properties, increasing demand on the lower-rent section of the Newham market and pricing our residents out.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Therefore it is increasingly difficult to house people with ties to the borough in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> let alone in Newham itself. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2.5</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Cuts to LHA are detrimental to working families in receipt of housing benefit and further restrict housing supply for those on low incomes. These changes have seen increased pressure on Newham’s homelessness service and increased hardship for local people.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> They drive down the standards of the local housing market – in particular we are concerned that it will encourage conversion of family homes to HMOs and leave families with little choice but to live in overcrowded accommodation. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2.6</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We believe that with</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">out sufficient resources to tackle the significant shortfall between LHA rates and market rents </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">we will experience an acute impact on our ability to place homeless households in the PRS in Newham.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">3. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Direct payment of housing costs to claimants</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.1</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">L</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ondon</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Borough of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Newham is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">anticipating a risk to revenues from the direct payment of housing costs under Universal Credit if tenants are unable to manage their finances effectively and fall into arrears. In particular we have concerns </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">that some vulnerable</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> claimants may be unable to manage regular rent payments. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The DWP have estimated that the financial risk to Newham would be 8% yet we believe this is a significant underestimation.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Newham believes the government’s evidence in support of this policy is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> misleading and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">does not properly report the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">early</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> findings from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">pilot</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> sites, which have shown increased risk of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> arrears.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This proposal will impact </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> income levels of social housing providers, Newham included, and will add the additional burden on local </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">authorities of increased rent collection activity which will need to be funded. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.3</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It is important that the findings from the pilot demonstration sites are reported and discussed in a transparent manner</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and take into account the levels of risk placed </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">on Local Authorities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> It must also be recognised that the pilots to date have not looked into the full spectrum of benefit recipients</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, meaning they may not be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> fully reflective of the population and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">not reflect the true level of risk. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">4. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Household benefit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> cap </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">4.1</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Whilst Newham agrees with the principle of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> cap, in reality it is making </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> unaffordable for those seeking work. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">F</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">amilies will be forced to move to areas of affordable rents where unemployment is high and prospects for employment are low. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">If the government is to continue this policy then work must be undertaken to promote employment in these areas.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">4.2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Additionally, Newham is concerned that the benefit cap represents a huge transfer of risk from central government to local authorities. Loc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">al authorities will have to deal with the costs in terms of lost rent, temporary accommodation and placement in alternative homes (often out-of-borough) and therefore we would support a higher benefit cap in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> areas.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">4.3</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Whilst the financial risk to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">local authorities occurs across a range of household types the risk is most acute in temporary accommodation provided for vulnerable households and those with young children. Those in temporary accommodation at the time of introduction</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">should be excluded </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">from the cap. Temporary accommodation is inevitably of a higher unit cost that will often exceed the cap level. If local authorities are expected to continue to di</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">scharge their homelessness duty, in or out of their own borough,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> it is arguable that all hous</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">eholds placed in temporary accommodation </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">should continue to be exempted, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">perhaps for a fixed period. However</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the most immediate pressure is on those in such accommodation at the time the cap is introduced. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">4.4</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">If a cap is to be introduced we believe tha</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t it should be phased in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">much </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">more slowly than currently proposed to give households time to adapt to the change</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">As outlined above the cost to local authorities in implementing new systems and dealing with resident queries will be significant at a time wh</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">en council budgets are already under extreme pressure. We believe that councils should be provided with additional transitional costs to implement these inevitable consequences of a shift in national policy. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">5. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Social sector size criteria </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">5</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.0</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Since the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> introduction of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">penalties for social housing under-occupancy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, there has been a surge in demand to our customer service centre. This has caused significant difficulties with resourcing to meet such demand. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">5.1</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Borough of Newham is concerned th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">at there is a lack of availability of suitable accommodation for people to move into if they are classed as living in houses that are too large for their needs. We believe that local authorities are left with insufficient resources to ensure residents are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">not penalised unnecessarily by this policy. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-33pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">5.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">As with the household benefit cap and direct payment of housing costs, we believe the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">spare room subsidy (known as the ‘bedroom tax’)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> constitutes a new burden on Local Authorities. Councils are expected to house families who are deemed to be over-accommodated into more suitable housing units.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> However, without access to more suitable properties there is an increasing the risk of arrears,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> adding to the financial pressure experienced by Councils. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-33pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">5.3</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Whilst we already have funding in place for mutual exchange programmes to allow them to make Local Authorities more attractive, we believe f</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">unding should be made available </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">for authorities to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> create </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">additional supply and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">deliver schemes to assist </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">“</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">home swap</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">”</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> building programmes.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We also believe that inconsistencies between policies relating to additional rooms for disabled adults and children </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">should be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">addressed immediately.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">6. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Localised cou</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ncil tax support</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">6.1</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Newham is worried that the resources allocated to deliver this policy are insufficient in terms of both programme and admini</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">stration budgets. This uncertain</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ty over funding makes the scheme very volatile and subject to change every </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">year. This proposal also represents a transfer of risk from central government to local authorities and the fixed level of funding does not take into account extra burdens placed upon local authorities or population increases. The money being transferred i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ncludes a 10% cut, which increases to 19% nationally and 15% in Newham (IFS estimate</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">) when pensioners are protected. Significantly, Newham is the largest growing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">borough in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> but this is not recognised in grants therefore putting a further unfair bur</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">den on authorities.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">6.2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We are concerned that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Government plans to provide local authorities with a fixed level of funding for Localised Council Tax Support, set at 90% of current expenditure, do not take into account additional properties which will becom</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e available throughout the first two year period.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">6.3</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In total 5,905 new housing units will be delivered in Newham up to and including 2014/15 according to our Core Strategy Housing trajectory, including the new E20 community in the Olympic Park. At least 35% will be 'affordable', meaning over 2000 new afford</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">able homes will be built in the area. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">It is therefore a realistic estimate that the number of individuals eligible to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">claim Council</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> Tax </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Support </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">under current rules could increase by 10% over the next 2 to 3 years.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> This is a key issue for us and we must emp</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">hasise that this change will heavily impact the council.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">6.4</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We are proud that as a council we are delivering new homes for residents. However the new system of Council Tax Support will penalise the council with an additional financial burden for deliveri</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ng affordable properties.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">6.5</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We are concerned that Localised Council Tax Support does not allow for in-year changes to the scheme, and is cash limited where previously it was covered by central government Annually Managed Expenditure. This means that if </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the level of applications increases against the expectations that we have budgeted for, we will have </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">find savings elsewhere rather than alter our scheme. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">6.6</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The set-up funding that has been offered to date for the administration of localised Council </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Tax Support has only been sufficient to cover the cost of software changes and consultation. No recognition has been given in this settlement of the cost of developing schemes on council officers’ time. No clarity has been offered over the level of funding</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> that will be provided in future years. This urgently needs to be resolved in a way that reflects the reality of extra burdens, such as appeal costs, that are being placed onto local authorities. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">6.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">7</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">These unfunded administration costs come at a time whe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">n we </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> one of only six local authorities to have our administration grant from the DWP reduced by the maximum of 10%, which along with a decrease in our special economic downturn grant totals over £500,000 in lost administrative budget. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">7. Conclusion</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he London Borough of Newham is concerned that the reforms proposed by the Department for Work and Pensions increase the risks and burdens placed upon local authorities. The lack of adequate funding to deal with these increased burdens will </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">mean that Newha</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">m’s residents are unfairly disadvantaged and we hope the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">G</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">overnment will take this on board and amend the proposals appropriately.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">27 September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> Monitoring the impact of changes to the Local Housing Allowance system of Housing Benefit: Interim report, 2013, DWP</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">IFS, ‘Reforming Council Tax Benefit’, 2012</span></p></body></html>